text: That's a good point. And I'd like to go back to the definition of the macro factors. So I guess there are two ways to define the macro factors. One way, which is very quanty. So imagine that you have all the assets in your markets and you're doing a form of principal component analysis. So you're trying to identify the latent factors which are driving the market dynamics. And you end up having a growth factor, a currency factor, a systemic risk factor, with monetary and fiscal policy factors. Most of cases with premire strategies are very much neutral to those factors because that's the way they are constructed. They're constructed as a long, short versions of those assets apart from short volatility strategies, for example. Because short volatility strategies have a lot of short volatility properties. And the short volatility of the short volatility have this correlation to the growth factor through their volatility and the correlation between markets and vol. So if you look at market factors defined like that, Swiss Premier Strategy tends to be relatively neutral. But if you look at long-term cycles, long-term macro cycles, if you think about recession, expansion, contraction, et cetera, or if you think about monetary cycle, which are long-term cycles, or if you think about price cycles like high-risk regime or low-risk regime, then you start to see differentiation in the strategies. So value, for example, tends to perform well in the risk-con environment and tends to underperform in the risk-off environment. Carry strategy tends to perform well in an accommodative monetary policy environment and tends to underperform in a tightening environment. So you do have... If you look at the long-term pictures of those factors, you start to see emerging some form of patterns, which in turn you can use to drive out the investments, depending on where you stand in the cycle. Now there's a big debate out there, which is timing versus non-timing factors. I think it's a famous quote from an asset manager and a guy from a research company. I'd say both are right and wrong. There's two things. There's the knowledge to be get to harvest from listening to a lot of different people. But what I've noticed is that in a world where all your strategies are performing really well, you don't care about timing. Because if you... Let's say you have a strategy that has a sharp ratio of one, and you mix a bunch of strategies which have a sharp ratio of one, then by the virtue of diversification, you'll get to some fantastic outcome. In a world where premium are compressed... And your average strategy may return something like two, three percent, while it was returning maybe six or seven percent before, you get your potential losses that are much higher. So you can do a much better job at trying to time your left tail, basically, because you have more occurrences of that left tail. In a world where premium are compressed, returns are challenged for whatever reason, being crowdness, being... Control banks, being other reasons, then knowing the macro behavior of those factors and adding a sense of timing in the platform construction process is very important and becomes more and more relevant. I think there's a great deal of things to be looked at when you look at those factors across cycles. Even if the measure is not perfect, even if this cycle is different to the next, definitely, the cycle... In is different. But at least you get some sort of knowledge of what can be happening in the future.
